  "interpretation": "In the 77-dim standardized feature space derived from 449 preflight runs, the Sinkhorn-regularized Wasserstein distance between the BLOCK cluster (n=175) and USE_MEMORY cluster (n=124) is W_eps = 13.479 (standardized) / 211580.717 (raw units). Sinkhorn converged in 6 iterations at epsilon=0.1. A barycenter biased 0.7 toward USE_MEMORY and 0.3 toward BLOCK (the 'safe recovery center') lies at mean L2 distance 10.57 sigmas from each BLOCK point (median=9.85, p95=17.82). The highest-leverage healing directions \u2014 features that must shift most in sigma-units to reach the barycenter \u2014 are led by `koopman.prediction_5` (delta=-1.61sigma), `lqr_control.optimal_control` (1.61sigma), `banach_contraction.fixed_point_estimate` (-1.61sigma). These are the components a repair plan should preferentially move to transport a BLOCKed memory state toward safety.",
  "notes": [
    "Pure numpy Sinkhorn implementation; cost matrix normalized by its max (matches repo scoring_engine/sinkhorn.py convention) before Gibbs kernel exp(-C/epsilon).",
    "Wasserstein reported in the *original* (un-scaled) cost units via sum(gamma * C).",
    "Barycenter is the simplified weighted mean (not the Wasserstein-barycenter fixed point) as specified: 0.3*mean(BLOCK) + 0.7*mean(USE_MEMORY).",
    "Feature matrix derived from live /v1/preflight on the 449-case benchmark corpus; BLOCK vs USE_MEMORY split by response.recommended_action."
